title: `$h_t_t_p::post()`
description: Return the `$_POST` data.
...

~~~ .php.xmp
HTTP::post($key = null, $fail = null, $eval = true);
~~~

**Example:**

~~~ .php
// `$_POST = ['user' => '@ta-tau-taufik', 'status' => '1']`

$test_1 = HTTP::post();
$test_2 = HTTP::post('user');
$test_3 = HTTP::post('status');
$test_4 = HTTP::post('status', null, false);
$test_5 = HTTP::post('pass');
$test_6 = HTTP::post('pass', 0);
~~~

Result:

~~~ .php
$test_1 = [
    'user' => '@ta-tau-taufik',
    'status' => 1
];

$test_2 = '@ta-tau-taufik';
$test_3 = 1;
$test_4 = '1';
$test_5 = null;
$test_6 = 0;
~~~

> **Note:** Values include `0`, `'0'`, and `' '` are considered not empty. So, returning a data contains these kind of value will not trigger the `$fail` value.